\description{
These generic functions define the base kernel, its needed derivatives, and
the score-coupling terms. New kernel classes can implement these methods and
then work with the rest of the package.
}
\details{
These functions are the pieces used by the full Stein kernel calculation in
\code{\link[=stein_kernel_matrix]{stein_kernel_matrix()}}. For rows \code{x_i = X[i, ]} and \code{y_j = Y[j, ]},
\code{eval_kernel()} gives the base kernel matrix
\deqn{K_{ij} = k(x_i, y_j).}
\code{grad_x_kernel()} gives first derivatives with respect to the first
argument,
\deqn{G_{ij\ell} = \partial k(x_i, y_j) / \partial x_\ell.}
\code{trace_mixed_kernel()} gives the matched second-derivative sum
\deqn{T_{ij} = \sum_{\ell = 1}^d
  \partial^2 k(x_i, y_j) / \partial x_\ell \partial y_\ell.}
\code{cross_kernel()} gives the two score-derivative terms
\deqn{C_{ij} =
s_p(x_i)^T \nabla_y k(x_i, y_j)
+ s_p(y_j)^T \nabla_x k(x_i, y_j).}
Then \code{\link[=stein_kernel_matrix]{stein_kernel_matrix()}} returns
\deqn{(s_p(x_i)^T s_p(y_j)) K_{ij} + C_{ij} + T_{ij}.}

\code{grad_theta_v_kernel()} is used by FSSD optimization. It gives the derivative
of the FSSD feature at one test location with respect to that location and,
for built-in kernels, with respect to the squared kernel scale.

These generics are not parallel top-level algorithms; they are a method
contract. A user who moves sideways from a built-in kernel to a custom S3
kernel must supply methods with the same shapes and the same row ordering.
A user who creates a kernel with \code{\link[=custom_stein_kernel]{custom_stein_kernel()}} supplies the same
information as functions instead of S3 methods. Either path lets the
top-level algorithms call \code{\link[=stein_kernel_matrix]{stein_kernel_matrix()}} and \code{\link[=compute_tau]{compute_tau()}} without
changing their own code.

These generics are public because they are the contract for kernel
extension. A user who only runs \code{\link[=ksd_u_test]{ksd_u_test()}} or \code{\link[=stein_points]{stein_points()}} normally
calls \code{\link[=stein_kernel]{stein_kernel()}} or \code{\link[=custom_stein_kernel]{custom_stein_kernel()}} instead. A user implementing
a new S3 kernel class can implement these methods and then reuse the package
algorithms without changing those algorithms.

The returned shapes are part of the contract: \code{eval_kernel()} and
\code{trace_mixed_kernel()} return matrices, \code{grad_x_kernel()} returns an
\verb{nrow(X) x nrow(Y) x d} array, \code{cross_kernel()} returns the matrix of the two
score-derivative terms, and \code{grad_theta_v_kernel()} returns the derivatives
needed by FSSD optimization.
